<HEAD>Allende Widow Leaves Mexico For Chile</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The widow of former Chilean President
Salvador Allende on Sunday left Mexico, where she has lived in
exile for 16 years, to return to live in Chile, the Mexican news
agency said.
   Mrs. Hortensia Bussi de Allende left for Santiago after thanking
the Mexican government for giving her asylum and suporting
democracy in Chile, said the state-run news service Notimex. Mexico
broke diplomatic relations with Chile after the overthrow of
Allende's elected Marxist government.
   ``Now we need more than ever the support and the unity of the
Chilean people and international help for the democratic transition
to be successful,'' Mrs. Allende told Notimex at Mexico City's
international airport.
   ``Chileans want to live in peace, with justice, liberty and
dignity,'' she added.
   Mrs. Allende left Chile after the Sept. 1973 coup that brought
to power the military dictatorship of Augusto Pinochet. Allende
died of a gunshot wound during the overthrow.
   The Pinochet government is being replaced March 11 by the
elected presidency of Patricio Aylwin.
   Mrs. Allende, 75, has visited Chile several times since 1988,
when the government lifted a ban on the return of exiles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

