<HEAD>Widow of Protagonist in Movie `Missing' Returns to Chile</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with more quotes, details; no pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Chile, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The widow of an American whose arrest and
slaying in a 1973 military coup inspired the movie ``Missing''
returned to Chile on Saturday to witness the end of Gen. Augusto
Pinochet's 16{-year rule.
   ``It's not the Chile of my nightmares,'' said Joyce Horman, who
was invited by the elected government that takes power Sunday.
   Mrs. Horman told The Associated Press in an interview that she
no longer expects any new information on her husband's death.
   ``I think it would be a very special circumstance for anyone
with direct knowledge to step forward at this time,'' she said. But
she added: ``I haven't ruled it out.''
   ``But the most important thing is that democracy is established
for Chileans, that there is respect for human rights.''
   Her husband, Charles Horman, then 29, was among thousands of
people arrested when Pinochet seized power in a bloody coup on
Sept. 11, 1973. It toppled the elected government of President
Salvador Allende, a Marxist. Horman, a free-lance journalist, and
his wife were living in Chile at the time.
   According to the family and testimony collected by human rights
groups, Horman was among many suspected dissidents held and
executed at Santiago's National Stadium. The military government
has denied the allegations.
   Horman's father, Ed Horman, pressed for years for details on his
son's death and wrote a book about his efforts. The book provided
the story for the movie ``Missing,'' starring Sissy Spacek as
Horman's wife and Jack Lemmon as the father.
   The movie is officially banned in Chile. ``Maybe now they'll
show it,'' Mrs. Horman said.
   In the AP interview, she said she found the country much more
open and friendly than it was when she and her father-in-law were
ushered out by U.S. diplomats and military authorities on Oct. 18,
1973.
   ``The air feels lighter. It's a different place,'' she said.
``It's not the place I remember.''
   Both Mrs. Horman, a 45-year-old computer specialist, and
Horman's father live in New York City. Horman's father is not
attending the inauguration.
   On Monday, the National Stadium will be the site of a massive
celebration to mark the end of Pinochet's rule.
   Patricio Aylwin, a 71-year-old Christian Democrat, was the
candidate of a center-left coalition that defeated Pinochet in Dec.
14 national elections, winning 55 percent of the vote.
   Mrs. Horman was one of about 400 people invited by Aylwin to
witness the change of government.
</TEXT>
