<HEAD>US-Chile Agreement a Major Step, State Department Negotiator Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One more step remains before US-Chilean
relations can be normalized, now that Chile has agreed to pay
compensation for the 1976 slaying in Washington of a Chilean
opposition figure and his aide, a U.S. negotiator says.
   The ``agreement in principle'' was concluded last week following
talks between Chilean and U.S. negotiators in Washington, State
Department legal adviser Abraham D. Sofaer said Sunday.
   He said the second step toward normalizing relations is to see
that the killers of Chilean exile leader Orlando Letelier and his
aide, Ronni Moffitt, are brought to justice. Letelier and Moffitt
died in a car bombing in Washington.
   ``Once we have both those things done, relations between both
these two countries can be completely normalized,'' Sofaer said.
``So it is very significant. It has taken us years to get here.''
   The agreement with the new government of Chilean President
Patricio Aylwin marks a reversal of the stance taken by Aylwin's
predecessor, right-wing Gen. Augusto Pinochet, who seized power in
the 1973 overthrow.
   Aylwin, who defeated a Pinochet-backed candidate in elections to
replace the military government, has promised full cooperation with
U.S. officials in the case. Aylwin took power in March.
   Sofaer underscored that Chile would make payments without
conceding any government liability for the death of Letelier, who
served in the government of Salvador Allende, a Marxist president
who died in a 1973 coup in Chile.
   ``We have agreed in principle to arbitration, in effect, to set
an amount of compensation to be paid to those people damaged by the
bombing,'' he said. The amount would be set by an international
tribunal.
   At the time of the Sept. 21, 1976, bombing, Letelier and Ms.
Moffitt were working for the Institute for Policy Studies. The
survivors include Letelier's widow and Ms. Moffitt's husband.
   A federal judge in 1980 concluded that the Pinochet government
and its agents were responsible for the deaths of Letelier and
Moffitt and ordered the Chilean government to pay $2.9 million in
compensation to the survivors.
   But the relatives have been unable to collect, and the United
States is expected to ask the tribunal to award at least the $2.9
million and 10 years' interest, The New York Times reported Sunday.
   In Chile, the issue of reparations has been seen as key battle
between Aylwin and Pinochet, who remains as army commander and has
promised to block human rights investigations of the military.
   Letelier served as ambassador to Washington and was foreign
minister during the Allende rule. In exile after the coup, he
became a severe critic of Pinochet's rule.
   Sofaer said the issue of civil payments is wholly separate from
criminal cases in the United States against former officials of the
Chilean secret police indicted in the killings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

