<HEAD>Widow of Allende Moves Back to Chile</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The widow of former President Salvador
Allende returned for good to her homeland Monday and said she would
attend the weekend ceremony in which Gen. Augusto Pinochet, who led
the coup that toppled her husband's government, gives up power.
   ``I want to spend my last years here,'' Hortensia Bussi de
Allende, 75, told reporters at Santiago's international airport.
She arrived from Mexico, where she lived for more than a decade in
exile.
   She was met by Socialist Party officials and by a daughter,
Isabel, and granddaughter, Marcia. A small crowd cheered her
arrival, which was virtually unpublicized.
   Mrs. Allende said she would attend Sunday's inaugural ceremony,
in which Pinochet hands over the presidency to an elected
successor, Patricio Aylwin, in the port city of Valparaiso.
   Asked if she planned to participate in the new government, she
replied: ``No. I've always said we have to make way for the younger
people.''
   Aylwin, a Christian Democrat, is backed by a coalition of 17
centrist and leftist parties, including the Socialist Party that
Allende once led.
   Mrs. Allende said she would lobby to have her husband's remains
moved to ``a deserved spot in Santiago, where everyone can pay him
homage, and to have a grand monument built.''
   Allende died in the presidential palace while it was being
bombarded by the military during a coup on Sept. 11, 1973.
According to witnesses, he committed suicide with a machine gun
when it became evident his leftist government was falling.
   He was buried in the unpretentious plot of a brother-in-law, in
the coastal resort of Vina del Mar, near Valparaiso. The military
kept the grave unmarked for many years.
   The military forced Mrs. Allende to leave the country within
days of the coup.
   She first returned in late 1988 after Pinochet, campaigning for
an eight-year extension of his rule, ordered an end to her exile
and that of hundreds of other dissidents. Voters in an October 1988
referendum rejected the extension for Pinochet, forcing him to call
elections.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

