<HEAD>Exiled Chilean Artists Now Can Work at Home</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting a0752 to include AM cycle designation</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EDUARDO GALLARDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Critics accused President Augusto
Pinochet on Friday of lifting the exile ban only to gain votes, but
whatever the motive, many Chilean artists and performers will be
able to work in their own country.
   Gen. Pinochet, who seeks to win eight more years in office as
the sole candidate in a presidential referendum Oct. 5, announced
Thursday that all 430 remaining political exiles may come home.
   One daughter of the late President Salvador Allende, overthrown
in the coup led by Pinochet in September 1973, already has returned
and Allende's widow and other daughter have said they will come
back.
   Among other people affected is Miguel Littin, an acclaimed movie
maker whose ``Acts of Marusia'' was nominated for an Academy Award
as the best foreign film of 1985. Littin and thousands of other
Chileans went into exile soon after the coup.
   It will not be Littin's first return. He spent several weeks
here in 1986 shooting scenes for a documentary on Chile, but he was
disguised, used an assumed name and posed as a member of an Italian
television crew.
   That film, ``General Act of Chile,'' is critical of the Pinochet
militry regime and has been shown at several European movie
festivals.
   An account of the secret visit was written later by Colombian
author Gabriel Garcia Marquez, a Nobel laureate and close friend of
Littin.
   Garcia Marquez wrote that Littin visited several Chilean cities
and on one occasion stood only a few yards from Pinochet while
filming a ceremony.
   On Friday, the Santiago newspaper La Epoca quoted Littin as
saying by telephone from his home in Madrid that he would return to
Chile ``in the next few hours, or in a week.''
   Littin now is shooting ``Sandino,'' a film about the late
Nicaraguan revolutionary leader Cesar Augusto Sandino with American
actor Dustin Hoffman playing the role of Sandino.
   Also expected to return is Helvio Soto, a movie maker who has
had been working in Paris.
   Two folk groups noted for protest songs, Inti Illimani and
Quilapallun, have performed successfully in Europe for years.
   Inti Illimani, now based in Rome, was on a U.S. tour when
Pinochet made his announcement.
   Quilapallun is based in Paris. It was not known if either group
planned to return.
   Patricio Manns, a folk musician who lives in Switzerland, also
can come back. In 1986 he became an ``international spokesman'' for
the Manuel Rodriguez Patriotic Front, Chile's main leftist
guerrilla group.
   Manns announced in Europe that the guerrillas claimed
responsability for the Sept. 6, 1986, attempt to assasinate
Pinochet, the army commander. The president escaped harm in the
ambush of his motorcade on a road in the Andes foothills near
Santiago but six bodyguards were killed and 11 wounded.
   La Epoca quoted Manns, also a poet and author, as saying he had
not decided whether to return and wanted ``security guarantees''
from the government.
   The Chilean Journalists Association said 32 journalists are
among the exiles affected. They include Jose Miguel Varas, a
communist who lives in Moscow and broadcasts a daily radio program,
``The Voice of Chile.''
</TEXT>
