<HEAD>U.S. Moving to Restore Relations With Democratic Chile</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States is moving to quickly
normalize relations with Chile's new democratic government, the
State Department said Thursday.
   This could include the lifting of economic sanctions and the end
of restrictions on military aid and arms sales.
   ``The United States applauds the return to democracy in Chile,''
the State Department said in a statement. ``We hope to normalize
quickly all of our relations with the new government in Chile,
including economic, political and defense relations.''
   The department's statement comes one month after the
inauguration of President Patricio Aylwin to replace dictator Gen.
Augusto Pinochet.
   Pinochet ruled Chile with an iron hand after the coup that
ousted Socialist President Salvador Allende Gossens in September
1973. Thousands of Allende's supporters were rounded up and many
were tortured or killed.
   Pinochet remains head of the Chilean armed forces.
   But Vice President Dan Quayle, who attended Aylwin's March 11
inauguration in Santiago, said Pinochet assured him he would follow
the policies of the new civilian government.
   The State Department said a review will open soon on Chile's
petition for the restoration of easier tariff treatment of its
exports and its request for renewed participation in the programs
of the Overseas Private Investment Corp.
   Chile was suspended from participation in these programs in 1987
due to workers' rights issues, the department said.
   Organized labor in Chile now strongly supports the ending of the
sanctions, the department said.
   Military aid and arms sales to Chile have been restricted since
1976. The department noted U.S. law bars their restoration until
the Chilean government meets these two conditions:
   _Restores respect for human rights.
   _Cooperates with the United States in bringing to justice those
Chilean intelligence officials suspected of complicity in the 1976
murders in Washington of former Chilean diplomat Orlando Letelier
and an American colleague, Ronni K. Moffitt.
   ``We are confident that the new government of Patricio Aylwin
will make every effort to meet those conditions,'' the department
statement said.
</TEXT>
