<HEAD>Chile, Mexico Renew Diplomatic Relations After 15{ Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chile and Mexico renewed diplomatic
relations Friday, more than 15 years after they were broken in
protest over the violent military coup that ousted elected
President Salvador Allende.
   A ceremony marking the restoration of diplomatic ties was
attended by Mexican President Carlos Salinas de Gortari and his
Chilean counterpart Patricio Aylwin.
   Mexico severed relations with Chile in November 1974 in protest
over the coup the previous year led by Gen. Augusto Pinochet. The
right-wing army commander gave up power 12 days ago and was
suceeded by Aylwin, an elected civilian politician.
   Gortari is scheduled to leave Saturday for Ecuador.
   In a brief speech, Aylwin thanked ``the Mexican government and
people for its solidarity with thousands of Chilean exiles'' who
lived in Mexico during Pinochet's rule.
</TEXT>
