<HEAD>Chile Signs Agreement with U.S. to Pay Compensation on Letelier
Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDUARDO GALLARDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chilean official said Saturday that his
government reached agreement with the United States to pay
compensation for the 1976 killing of a Chilean opposition figure
and a U.S. associate in Washington.
   The ``agreement in principle'' came Friday in a meeting between
Chilean and U.S. officials in Washington, said acting Interior
Minister Belisario Velasco.
   He gave few details on the agreement.
   Velasco said the payments would go to the families of Orlando
Letelier, a former Chilean foreign minister who fled to the United
States following a 1973 right-wing military coup, and Ronni
Moffitt, an aide to Letelier who also was killed when their car was
bombed in Washington.
   ``In the next few days, a complete announcement with details
will be made,'' said Velasco in an interview. He said the matter
must now be taken to President Patricio Aylwin, a civilian who
replaced Gen. Augusto Pinochet in March.
   Pinochet led the 1973 overthrow of elected civilian President
Salvador Allende, and his military government had blocked efforts
by U.S. courts and the government to seek compensation in the
killings.
   Velasco said the meeting in Washington was between Deputy
Foreign Minister Edmundo Vargas, Chile's ambassador to the United
States, Patricio Silva, and three U.S. officials _ Assistant
Secretary of State Bernard Aronson, Abraham Sofaer, the State
Department's legal adviser, and Charles Gillespie, the U.S.
ambassador to Chile.
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Mark Dillen said: ``I
can't confirm the agreement by the Chileans, but their deputy
foreign minister has been in town discussing bilaterial issues with
us and also meeting with the (Organization of American States).
   ``As of yesterday, what we were saying was that we're optimistic
our discussions would result in a satisfactory resolution to the
case.''
   The agreement was not expected to affect criminal cases in the
United States against former officials of Pinochet's secret police
indicted in the killings.
   Aylwin, who defeated a Pinochet-backed candidate in elections to
replace the military government, has promised full cooperation with
U.S. officials in the case.
   In Chile, the issue is seen as a key battle between Aylwin and
Pinochet, who remains as army commander and has promised to block
human rights investigations of the military.
   Letelier served as Chile's ambassador to Washington and was
foreign minister during the Allende government. In exile following
the 1973 coup, he became a severe critic of Pinochet's rule.
   At the time of the Sept. 21, 1976, Letelier and Ms. Moffitt were
working for the Institute for Policy Studies.
</TEXT>
