<HEAD>Widow of Marxist President Visits His Unmarked Grave</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VINA DEL MAR, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The widow of Salvador Allende visited
the president's unmarked grave Monday after returning from 15
years' forced exile, and tearfully thanked those who tended the
site in her absence.
   Hortensia Bussi de Allende made the 75-mile trip from Santiago,
the capital, to the Pacific coastal resort town of Vina del Mar
with her two daughters, Isabel and Carmen, and a grandson, Gonzalo.
   Mrs. Allende, 74, spent a few minutes in silence before the
gravestone, which carried only the name of a sister, Ines, and a
brother-in-law. A recently-placed plaque bearing Allende's name had
been removed.
   She brought a bouquet of red carnations and left them atop the
tomb.
   About two dozen sympathizers, most of them working-class women,
embraced Mrs. Allende at the hillside cemetery. Many said they
regularly tended to the gravesite.
   The widow, brushing back tears, told the women, ``I thank all of
you for your faithfulness.''
   ``Faithful to the death,'' several women answered.
   On a concrete walkway in front of the tomb, supporters had
written in red paint: ``Allende Lives On In The People.''
   Mrs. Allende returned to Chile Saturday, 24 days after
right-wing President Augusto Pinochet announced an end to all
official exile. The measure affected 504 leftists, including Mrs.
Allende and her children.
   Allende died on Sept. 11, 1973, during a coup led by Gen.
Pinochet that toppled the elected leftist government. According to
the military, Allende shot himself with a machine gun at the
presidential palace, which was rocketed by air force fighter jets.
The version is widely accepted by historians and even many Pinochet
critics. Allende, a Marxist, had said he would never surrender or
allow himself to be captured.
   A day later, he was buried in Vina del Mar. Mrs. Allende was
flown by the military to attend the ceremony. She and her children
then sought refuge in the Mexican Embassy in Santiago and left the
country.
   Mrs. Allende was not active in her husband's government but
after his death became a symbol of political repression by the new
military government. She became an outspoken critic of Pinochet,
and upon her return said she would support efforts to defeat him in
an Oct. 5 presidential plebiscite.
   If a majority votes yes in the ballot, Pinochet will remain in
power until 1997. If most vote no, an open election will be held
next year and he must hand power over to the winner in 1990.
</TEXT>
