<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Augusto Pinochet called for
support from opposition leaders on Wednesday after violent protests
followed his nomination as the only candidate in an October
presidential referendum.
   Authorities said hundreds were arrested during widespread
rioting Tuesday and three people were killed, including two
teen-age boys, as residents threw open their windows and banged
pots and pans in defiance.
   Rioting in the streets broke out after the military junta
nominated Pinochet, who took part in the selection process, to be
the sole nominee in an October presidential referendum.
   In a nationally broadcast address Wednesday night, Pinochet made
a rare appeal for opposition backing. In previous addresses, he has
dismissed opponents as ``traitors,'' ``rats,'' ``highwaymen'' and
``cowards.''
   ``Our democracy needs the collaboration of all Chileans,'' he
said. ``I call today on my compatriots, supporters and opponents,
to assume this noble task. Chile needs you.''
   The remarks followed huge demonstratons by thousands of people
in the capital and elsewhere.
   In Santiago alone, 846 protesters were arrested during the
day-long street demonstrations and clashes, a report from the
national police said. It gave no precise figure for arrests outside
the capital, although scores were reported arrested in protests in
most other cities.
   Many of those arrested were being released Wednesday after an
identity check, some without being charged and others cited to
appear before city judges.
   The national police said the dead included two boys, age 14 and
15, and an adult. It said 21 people were injured in the rioting.
   Pinochet, who commands the army, has led the military government
that has governed Chile since September 1973, when the elected
government of Marxist President Salvador Allende was overthrown in
a bloody coup by the armed forces. Allende died in the coup.
   Pinochet was picked in a meeting with the chiefs of the navy,
air force and national police to be the sole candidate in an Oct. 5
presidential referendum.
   If a majority vote in his favor, he will assume a new eight-year
term on March 11. If voters reject him, he remains in power until
1990 when an open presidential election is to be held in conjuction
with elections for a Congress.
   The nomination came despite appeals by the local Roman Catholic
church and several moderate political organizations for a candidate
who would have the backing of both the government and opposition.
   It also ended speculation that the other commanders, who had
publicly expressed support for a civilian nominee, would insist
that Pinochet give up his army commandership in return for the
candidacy.
   The formal nomination declaration refers repeatedly to Pinochet
as army leader and the army commander pointedly made his acceptance
speech in military uniform.
   He can legally remain army leader if he wins the referendum and
remains president.
   Opposition leaders, meanwhile, said that Pinochet's nomination
will backfire.
   `This confrontational decision directly compromises the armed
forces, who will suffer from his defeat in the plebescite,''
Patricio Aylwin, leader of the centrist Christian Democratic Party,
said Wednesday of Pinochet's selection.
   The opposition cites several opinion polls that give a 2-1
advantage to Pinochet opponents in the ballot.
Government-contracted polls give him a slight edge in the vote.
   Speaking to foreign reporters, Aylwin said Pinochet's army
commandership ``acts as a kind of shield, and exerts moral pressure
on his institution.''
   ``Pinochet is too attached to power, and I don't believe he is
willing to give up any of his priveleges,'' he said.
   Aylwin described ``as generally peaceful'' Tuesday's
anti-government protests, in which thousands of people
participated. But he said he expected that the incidents of
violence would be politically exploited by Pinochet's
administration.
   Interior Minister Sergio Fernandez issued a declaration
Wednesday that blamed the violence on the political opposition.
``Once again, extremist groups have sewed death and fear. Those
responsible for these acts are clearly identified with the
(supports of a) vote of `no.'
   Christian Democrat vice-president Andres Zaldivar said, however,
``The only violence occurred where there was police repression.''
Riot police squads had broken the demonstrations with tear gas and
water cannon.
   Aylwin described one of Tuesday's falities, that of a
15-year-old boy, as ``one more youth added to the victims of the
dictatorship.'' The boy was participating in a pot-banging protest
when he was shot twice in the chest by gunmen in a passing car.
   A 1980 Constitution crafted by the Pinochet government calls for
a phased return to democracy, including a resumption of Congress in
1990. However, about a third of the senate would government
appointees and high-ranking military officials. The Congress also
   A declaration signed by leaders of a 16-party opposition
coalition Wednesday reaffirmed their plans to campaign for a vote
of ``no''in the referendum and, if they win, to negotiate with the
armed forces for constitutional changes.
