<LEADPARA>  Agents of the 17-year military regime led by Gen. Augusto Pinochet killed
2,025 Chileans, according to a comprehensive report released Monday
chronicling human-rights abuses during the 1973-'90 rule of Pinochet. In
releasing the report, which was prepared during the last year by a blue-ribbon
commission, President Patricio Aylwin said in Santiago that there was no
justification for the killings and torture and said, "Justice demands . . .
the determination of the persons responsible.";    The report finds that
Salvador Allende, the Socialist president overthrown by Pinochet in a Sept.
11, 1973, coup, committed suicide inside the presidential palace as Pinochet's
forces were storming the gates. Opponents of the military regime insisted for
years that Allende had been slain, but the commission found that Allende shot
himself to honor a promise he made in his final radio address, to "repay the
loyalty of the people with my life."  </LEADPARA>
